<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / The Lex Column: Retailing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
If the stock market is any guide, Britain's shopkeepers have shrugged off
tax rises and are expecting consumers to carry on spending with abandon.
Since February, the stores sector has been among the market's most
resilient. That may partly reflect negative reasoning: investors have viewed
stores as a safe haven as storms have raged in other markets. Marks and
Spencer, Boots and GUS, which account for 60 per cent of sector
capitalisation, are dependable stocks with cast-iron balance sheets, high
quality earnings and marginal overseas exposure.
But the other great appeal of shops is they are seen as a good hedge against
inflation. That was undoubtedly true in the 1970s but it might not prove to
be the case today. In mature competitive industries, modest inflation is
hard to pass on to customers - as the grocery industry has already shown.
Retailers' earnings will be squeezed by other pressures, too. Many groups
have announced big investment plans, threatening to add capacity in excess
of sales volume growth. Landlords will also become less generous with rent
discounts while foreign entrants to the market are turning up the
competitive heat.
The stores sector undoubtedly has great potential for generating surplus
cash. That raises the possibility of dividend increases or special pay-outs.
But the sector would have to raise its collective yield substantially to
match the market average. It is also somewhat quirky for retailers to stand
on both earnings and dividend premiums at the same time.
</TEXT>
