<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Fund managers warned on costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The profitability of the UK fund-management industry reached a six-year peak
last year because of buoyant markets, but the industry's costs are also
rising far faster than they should, a survey by Price Waterhouse concludes.
In its sixth annual review of the fund-management industry the accountancy
and management consultancy group says that pre-tax profits as a proportion
of total revenues rose to 28.8 per cent last year, up from 18.1 per cent in
1992. None of the 41 organisations in the survey reported a pre-tax
operating loss last year, compared with a third in 1992.
The study found that costs rose on average by 4 per cent more than was
needed to accommodate expenses associated with the rise in assets under
management.
The report concludes: 'While other industries have achieved productivity
improvements over the last five years, it appears that the investment
mangement industry has had a negative productivity improvement.'
Investment Management Survey 1994, Price Waterhouse Management Consultants,
Milton Gate, 1 Moor Lane, London EC2Y 9PB. Free.
</TEXT>
