<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Group to press for 'lookalike' curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Representatives of more than 30 leading brand manufacturers will tomorrow
formalise a campaign group to press for legislation curbing supermarkets'
'lookalike' brands, Neil Buckley writes.
The British Producers and Brand Owners Group, set up earlier this year,
failed to get clauses included in the Trademarks Bill to strengthen
restrictions on lookalikes  - own-label products designed to resemble
well-known brands.
The main aim of the group, which includes Unilever, Mars and Nestle, will be
to persuade the government to introduce legislation.
It may also investigate the possibility of taking action against
supermarkets under European Union law.
Own-label products account for more than 50 per cent of sales by volume in
supermarket chains. Brand manufacturers want legislation to stop
supermarkets not only infringing registered trademarks, but copying the
overall look of branded goods, including the colour and shape of packaging.
</TEXT>
