<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Parking duty passes to councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A parking system which removes responsibility for enforcement from the
police and hands it to local authorities comes into effect throughout London
today.
Parking infringements will no longer be treated as criminal offences but
will be dealt with as an administrative issue by the local authorities and,
if necessary, as a civil matter in the county courts.
The system has been introduced in the 33 London boroughs but three-quarters
of local authorities around the country have expressed an interest in
adopting it. The Parking Committee for London said the idea was borrowed
from US cities such as Chicago and Philadelphia, but was its first example
in Europe.
The government believes parking regulations will be enforced more
effectively while a burden is removed from the police. Local authorities can
spend any surplus from fines on improving parking facilities, upgrading
roads or public transport.
Traffic wardens will be replaced by local-authority parking attendants who
will enforce parking laws with the help of hand-held computers. They will
issue penalty-charge notices for Pounds 30, Pounds 40 or Pounds 60.
One feature of the system is that prompt settlement is encouraged by
discounts of 50 per cent if a ticket is paid within 14 days. Under the Road
Traffic Act of 1991 councils also have the power to tow away or clamp
vehicles.
Under the previous rules police in London issued up to 2m parking tickets a
year, but at one stage fewer than half were paid.
Motorists who feel they have been unjustly treated may take their case to an
independent tribunal known as the Parking Appeals Service. Instead of being
summoned to a magistrates court motorists will be able to make an
appointment at a time which suits them.
The 1,500 traffic wardens employed by the police in London will be
redeployed to enforce no-stopping rules on the 'red routes' which are being
introduced to speed traffic throughout London.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
