<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Tax rules for Peps attacked by insurers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The favourable tax treatment of Personal Equity Plans has come under fire
from the Association of British Insurers, which has called on the government
to introduce a tax regime which does not direct savings into particular
investments.
The plea has been made in a private response to the Treasury as part of the
government's review of savings.
The association says tax breaks, if required, should be directed towards
longer-term savings.
It contrasts the tax neutrality towards which the government seemed to be
moving until the mid-1980s as tax breaks were ended, with the policy since
then of creating savings vehicles which can be tax-free.
An individual can invest up to Pounds 9,000 a year in Peps, by putting
Pounds 6,000 into a general Pep and Pounds 3,000 into a single company Pep.
Sales of Peps are estimated to have reached Pounds 6bn in 1993-94.
According to an ABI analysis the net income which a Pep can generate for
basic and higher-rate taxpayers is greater than that which can come from any
other capital sum, including personal pensions.
It notes that in practice pensions and Peps are not in direct competition in
the savings market, but highlights the advantage which the tax treatment
gives Peps over putting money into equities, unit trusts and life insurance.
The ABI paper makes the case for continuing the favourable tax treatment of
savings through pension schemes.
It says that given public concern about life companies' attitudes to
regulatory standards and about the possible mis-selling of products, there
would appear to be little political attraction for the government in
introducing new tax breaks for life insurance.
However, greater equality between different forms of savings might be
achieved by imposing new limits on the amounts that can be invested tax-free
in Peps and Tessas  - tax-exempt special savings accounts.
Mr Stephen Dorrell and Mr Anthony Nelson, the Treasury ministers leading the
exercise, have held several meetings with interested parties to seek their
views, but no decisions are likely to be announced until the Budget on
November 29.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
