<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Financial malpractice in the workplace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Businesses could learn from practices developed in the US and reward staff
for highlighting financial malpractice in the workplace, a report says
today, Richard Donkin writes.
The report, by Public Concern at Work, an organisation which advises
workplace 'whistleblowers', says fraud and financial malpractice have been
the most prevalent concerns of employees who have approached it for advice.
The report says: 'Our impression is that the pervading culture in many
organisations in the UK is that staff should mind their own business come
what may.'
It says this is in contrast to developments in the US, where companies have
started to reward staff for minding the company's business. The report cites
Bear Sterns, the New York stockbroker, which gives staff 5 per cent of any
losses they prevent when they report financial malpractice.
</TEXT>
