<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Baked-bean contender launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Alistair Grant, group chairman of Safeway, is said to be passionate
about it. He and his colleagues believe it can make a significant
contribution to cutting Britain's food-trade deficit.
The humble baked bean does not normally elicit such excitement but a new,
home-grown variety has captured the imagination of the food industry,
farmers and the Ministry of Agriculture. Such beans are normally imported
from North America.
The public will have its first chance to taste the British contender at the
Royal Show, England's biggest agricultural event, which opens today at
Stoneleigh in Warwickshire.
The appropriately named Albion variety of the navy bean - the raw material
for baked beans in tomato sauce - is being launched by Safeway, which hopes
to use it in its own-label product as part of its policy of import
substitution.
Baked beans were first imported into Britain by the Pittsburgh-based company
HJ Heinz at the turn of the century and sold at Fortnum &amp; Mason as a
delicacy. They became a cheap and popular staple food once Heinz started to
manufacture in the UK in 1928. Britons now consume 900m cans a year, or
about 16 cans per head, with sales totalling Pounds 230m.
To meet this huge demand the UK has to import 85,000 tonnes of navy beans
from the US and Canada at a cost of about Pounds 40m. Recent trials at
Cambridge University have shown that Albion and other new varieties can
survive cold, wet English summers and stand up to comparison with their
North American rivals.
Mr Geoffrey Gent, director of the Processors and Growers Research
Organisation, a group of farmers and food companies sponsoring the trials,
said: 'Last year was a critical testing time for the new generation of
beans. They developed well, maintaining a high level of quality despite a
summer of poor weather.
'We believe there is potential for the UK to compete internationally for
navy bean production.'
The project's supporters are campaigning for financial support from the
European Union under the Common Agricultural Policy.
The value of the basic crop is higher than that of comparable peas and field
beans, but it is uneconomical for farmers to grow because it does not
qualify for subsidies of Pounds 365 a hectare.
</TEXT>
