<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / OECD set to slam Pergau arms link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British government's use of an offer of Pounds 234m worth of aid to
Malaysia to help build the Pergau dam is expected to be criticised by the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development when it publishes a
long-delayed report tomorrow.
The report is expected to be broadly complimentary about the general conduct
of British aid policy. But it is thought to be critical about the way that
aid was linked to a defence deal in the case of the Pergau dam project.
The OECD's criticisms will come when the political controversy over
Britain's aid programme for the dam is set to re-open.
The Commons foreign affairs committee is due to publish a report into the
Pergau project in a few weeks. It is expected to be critical of decisions
taken by Baroness Thatcher's government in the late 1980s.
Later in the year the High Court will decide whether to issue a judicial
review of the decision by Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, to proceed
with the aid deal in 1991. If the High Court issued a review it could order
a halt to the bulk of the Pounds 234m of payments to the Malaysian
government.
The OECD's report is being published by the organisation's development
assistance committee following an annual review of Britain's aid programme
by a team of Finnish and Belgian examiners.
The OECD has been criticised for delaying the report, which was completed in
draft form in March. OECD officials have blamed the delay on production
difficulties.
In discussing Britain's involvement in Malaysia the committee is thought to
have expressed unanimous support for the principle that all aid be subjected
to the full standards of normal assessment and that 'aid quality should
predominate' in decisions by individual member states.
OECD examiners have taken evidence from British officials at the Overseas
Development Administration, which manages Britain's aid programme. Civil
servants objected to the Pergau project on economic grounds but were
overruled by ministers.
The government changed its aid and trade rules last year.
The aid grant offer to Malaysia was the largest ever provided for a single
scheme under the government's aid and trade provision.
</TEXT>
