<TEXT>
The natural order of western European soccer re-asserted itself when Germany
and Spain disposed of Belgium and Switzerland on Saturday with no more than
a modicum of fuss. Germany beat Belgium 3-2 and Spain beat Switzerland 3-0.
The German result in an unseasonably cool Chicago was also closer than the
balance of play warranted. Albert's 90th-minute goal set up a frantic
finish, with Preud'homme, the admirable Belgian 'keeper, up in the German
penalty area and almost geting his head to an injury-time cross.
Belgian appeals for a second-half penalty after Weber had been brought down
were waved away.
Klinsmann, maintaining his goal-a-game pace, and Voller were too quick and
co-ordinated for the Belgian defence.
