<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / North Yemen oil output halted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
North Yemen's 190,000 barrel a day oil production has been halted by a south
Yemeni air raid, a north Yemeni oil official said at the weekend. The attack
deprives the Sanaa government of its chief source of hard currency until the
damage is repaired.
Northern forces, meanwhile, kept up artillery and rocket attacks on the
southern city of Aden as the International Committee of the Red Cross warned
that people in the city would soon be dying of thirst unless its shelled
water treatment plant was repaired.
Witnesses and hospital officials said 17 people were killed yesterday in the
shelling of Aden's residential areas, including nine who were digging a well
for water. Up to 23 people were injured.
North Yemeni officials last night said the northern government would let the
ICRC send water trucks to Aden and has promised safe passage to engineers to
repair installations.
Mr Ismail al-Dailami, oil ministry manager at Marib, told Reuters that a
raid by southern jets last week had destroyed two vital water coolers at the
crude oil pumping station feeding the pipeline to Ras Isa, the north's oil
export terminal.
He said that the damage could be repaired 'in a few days'. But it was
unclear if replacements for the two wrecked coolers were available in Yemen
or would have to be flown into the country.
The Marib operation is the mainstay of north Yemen's oil industry, pumping
almost 190,000 b/d of crude. Production is continuing in the south, where
Canadian Occidental is producing up to 160,000 b/d from its Masila field,
but the company has been paying Yemen's share of the oil revenues into a
trust account since the outbreak of civil war in early May.
</TEXT>
