<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Moves on European pensions directive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The European Union, in an effort to break the deadlock over a European
pensions directive, is considering an alternative non-obligatory
'recommendation' urging the liberalisation of pension investment rules in
member states.
Speaking at a seminar on European pension provision, Mr Ron Golby, a
technical adviser to DGXV, the EU division which drafted the pension
directive, said that 'an alternative' could take the form of a
recommendation. The recommendation would be non-binding, although aggrieved
parties could ask the European Court of Justice to enforce compliance. It
would be up to the ECJ to decide whether it wished to enforce the
recommendation.
In June, the EU's Internal Market Council rejected a draft directive aimed
at loosening member states' restrictions on the types of assets and
currencies in which their domestic pension funds could invest. The measure
was intended to grant funded pension schemes the authority to invest in a
mix of assets which would yield the highest returns.
However, several member states which restrict pension investment to the home
country's currency or to its own government bonds, objected.
Meanwhile, a report commissioned by the EU from a group of pensions experts
noted that 'the draft directive has probably helped to reveal and to fuel a
latent conflict of interest between EU member states'. Mr Giovanni Tamburi,
a consultant with actuarial consultants R Watson and one of the authors of
the report, argued that the directive had been far too ambitious to succeed.
Because the style of pension investment has little bearing on competition,
the EU would be wiser to allow each member state to adopt its own investment
philosophy. 'The EU should use the concept of a framework of principles and
let member countries decide the matter between themselves,' the report said.
However, Mr Golby denied that the EU had been too ambitious, although it may
have made some errors. 'With the benefit of hindsight, some issues could
have been handled better.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
