<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Russian oil giant entices west
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lukoil, Russia's largest oil company, will offer more than 20 per cent of
its shares to the public and a further 15 per cent to foreign investors
within the country's second round of privatisations which began at the
weekend.
Lukoil, which produces approximately 50m tonnes of oil a year, 15 per cent
of total Russian crude, from western Siberia is the first large oil company
to offer shares to western investors.
The company has been the main beneficiary of the break-up of the old Rosneft
holding company and has inherited unquantified reserves which it claims to
be among the largest in the world.
In the past six months the company has frozen the price of its products and
lowered production costs by cutting out layers of management and reducing
drilling and repair teams.
It is also investing in a new refinery in association with the Swiss-Swedish
ABB Brown Boveri power engineering company, at Krasnodar, in southern
Russia, near the oil port of Novorossisk. Mr Vagit Alegperov, the company's
president, noted that the distance of existing refineries from the ports
increased transport costs.
The company's strategy is to turn itself into a competitive energy company
with associates in the former Soviet states as well as abroad. It has taken
a 10 per cent share in the BP-led consortium to develop oil reserves off
Azerbaijan - a project which Mr Alegperov said should be ready for Azeri
government approval by September.
However, oil quotas, which should have been lifted on July 1, will stay in
place at least until next January, according to Mr Oleg Davydov, the Russian
trade minister.
He said that the measure was 'untimely' because of the need to ensure fuel
for vital projects such as harvesting.
Energy production in Russia fell sharply in the first six months of the year
 -oil by more than 14 per cent, coal by 10.4 per cent, electricity by 6.5
per cent and gas by 2 per cent, compared with the same period last year. The
Energy Ministry blamed the fall on the debt crisis which has seen energy
companies run up debts of nearly Rbs40,000bn by June 1 as credit was cut or
priced too high for the enterprises to borrow.
The debt crisis is also held responsible for the widespread delays in
payments to oil workers, many of whom have received no wages for up to six
months.
A hunger strike has started by oil workers in Usinsk, in the norther Komi
Republic, because of a backlog of wages to February this year.
Mr Mikhail Shmakov, head of the Independent Trade Unions of Russia, said
that the situation in the oil fields could 'get out of hand' if the wages
backlog were not addressed.
</TEXT>
