<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / SPD and Greens near Saxony-Anhalt accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Social Democratic party (SPD) was yesterday edging towards a minority
government with the Green party in the eastern German state of
Saxony-Anhalt, a move which will require the tacit support of the Party of
Democratic Socialism (PDS), the reformed East German Communist party.
Mr Reinhard Hoppner, the SPD leader in Saxony-Anhalt, said negotiations were
in progress to clear the way for the formation of a state government.
He had earlier rejected the idea of forming a so-called 'grand coalition'
between the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and the SPD, the two biggest
parties in the state parliament.
The SPD said it had opted for the so-called red-green coalition, regarded by
many as a risky experiment, to show that it was serious about winning the
general elections in October and would not accept any pacts with the CDU. If
the experiment in Saxony-Anhalt works it could bolster the SPD which is now
trailing the CDU in most opinion polls.
However, the closer ties between the SPD and the PDS will give Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats valuable political ammunition in the
run-up to the October elections, allowing them to cast the SPD as allies of
a party which is regarded by many people in western Germany as unacceptable.
In Bavaria the PDS is ranked alongside the far-right Republicans and both
are under surveillance by the interior ministry.
Mr Theo Waigel, the finance minister and leader of the Christian Social
Union, the Bavarian equivalent of the CDU, opened what is likely to be a
barrage of criticism by accusing the SPD of giving a 'helping hand to the
drawing-room Bolsheviks'.
The CDU emerged as the biggest party in the state elections last week with
37 seats in the state parliament.
The SPD has 36 seats, the PDS 21 and the left-wing Greens five.
</TEXT>
