<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Geneva talks on new map of Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International mediators convene in Geneva today to put the finishing touches
on a 'take-it-or-leave-it' plan for Bosnia's partition. The plan's
architects - from Russia, the US, the UK, Germany, and France - propose
giving 51 per cent of Bosnia to the new Moslem-Croat federation and the
remainder to the Serbs, who currently control 70 per cent of the war-torn
country. Foreign ministers from the five-nation 'contact group' are due to
meet tomorrow to endorse the maps.
Leaders of the rival factions are also set to discuss the maps which have
already come under criticism.
Bosnian and Croatian foreign ministers, meeting in the Turkish capital
Ankara on Saturday, gave only qualified endorsement to the peace plan.
Bosnia's foreign minister, Mr Irfan Ljubiankic, said his government would
'not be the first to reject the plan', stressing however that the most
important issue was the 'quality of the territory and the guarantees for the
implementation of the plan'.
A joint communique warned that Bosnia and Croatia would reject any peace
plan that failed 'to redress the consequences of acquisitions of territories
through the use of force and ethnic cleansing'. But Mr Radovan Karadzic,
Bosnian Serb leader, dismissed as 'humiliating' the maps which he said would
prolong the war.
'If the current proposals are not changed, we should finally cancel our
co-operation with this worldwide mafia . . . we should deny them the right
to regulate Serb states,' he said.
Diplomats say the plan represents a 'last chance' for the warring sides to
decide whether they want 'carrots or sticks' from the international
community, united behind the newest maps. Measures could include the lifting
of sanctions on Belgrade, imposed for Bosnia's violent carve-up, or ending
the arms embargo on the Bosnian government.
Sources in Belgrade said that President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia was
'taking the peace plan seriously'. He may exert pressure on his Bosnian
proxies in order to win the lifting of UN sanctions.
</TEXT>
