<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Rail union leaders set to call for further negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The leaders of RMT, Britain's main rail union, are today likely to call for
a resumption in negotiations to resolve the signalling staff dispute that
has cost Railtrack Pounds 30m in lost revenue through three one-day strikes.
The union's executive of 21 is likely to announce plans for further 24-hour
stoppages after its meeting this afternoon. It will also discuss calls for
an escalation of the dispute through longer stoppages.
Railtrack, the state-owned company in charge of the network's
infrastructure, says the men  - traditionally a moderate group  - want a
settlement and not further stoppages.
But some union officials fear the company's 'hearts and minds' campaign to
convince the signalling staff to accept its three-stage productivity deal
might harden attitudes.
The union's rejection of the deal as it stands may be reinforced by
confirmation tomorrow that British Rail has substantially reduced its
operating deficit to about Pounds 100m for last year, down from an operating
loss of Pounds 167m in the year before.
Both sides made clear last night that they would like to resume negotiations
as soon as possible. Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT's general secretary, and Mr Bob
Horton, Railtrack chairman, are to give evidence tomorrow before the House
of Commons employment committee. They are expected to use the opportunity to
emphasise their desire to settle what has turned into an intractable and
complex dispute.
However, further negotiations are likely to come too late to prevent this
Wednesday's 24-hour strike, the fourth in as many weeks.
In spite of outward signs of deadlock, RMT officials and Railtrack hinted
yesterday that the gap between them might not be as unbridgeable as it has
looked for the past four weeks. BR is also expected to report that it spent
an estimated Pounds 100m in the past financial year in preparing for the
privatisation of the railway network, nearly double its previous estimate.
The total cost of privatising the railways is believed to have risen to more
than Pounds 600m.
The dramatic improvement in BR's business performance is mainly due to a 7
per cent cut in railway operating costs.
A union official said yesterday it would have cost Railtrack Pounds 5m to
meet the RMT's 11 per cent interim pay demand for signalling staff. A
spokesman said the RMT wanted negotiations to focus upon possible
improvements to Railtrack's offer.
Politics obstructs line to peace in signals dispute, Page 7
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
