<DATE>940702
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / Finance and the Family: The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This week sees full-year figures from two brewers, one national, one
regional. Monday's results from Scottish &amp; Newcastle will be scrutinised
closely for evidence of early progress from Chef &amp; Brewer, which S&amp;N bought
from Grand Metropolitan late last year.
The Pounds 703m deal was of strategic importance to S&amp;N, since it greatly
increased its pub estate in the south of England and gave it an important
new outlet for its beer. On the other hand, GrandMet has the reputation of
extracting top prices for businesses it sells. Forecasts are for S&amp;N to have
profits of about Pounds 230m pre-tax against Pounds 201m.
Full-year results from Greene King, the East Anglian regional brewer, are
due on Thursday. The market is unsure of its ground, since Greene King's
interim results were particularly disappointing with profits almost
unchanged. Since then, the shares have been among the weakest in the sector,
underperforming the market by around 15 per cent. Last year's pre-tax
profits were Pounds 20.1m, down from Pounds 20.3m the year before. Any
improvement in the headline figure this time will be regarded as progress.
MFI, the furniture group, is expected on Monday to announce a big increase
in full-year, pre-tax profits from Pounds 40.2m to about Pounds 70m.
Analysts raised their forecasts from about Pounds 60m after MFI's interim
results in January, when it disclosed a much stronger performance in the
January sales than in 1993. They are keen to hear from MFI whether the
improvement has been sustained. Exceptional charges of Pounds 214m connected
with the sale of its Silo chain in the US will obscure a small fall in
underlying profits at Dixons, the UK's largest electrical retailer, on
Wednesday. Before the charges - which include trading and disposal losses,
and a Pounds 191m goodwill write-off - pre-tax profits are forecast at about
Pounds 75m. Last year's figure, after provisions for losses at Silo and
other charges, was Pounds 33.5m, but before exceptionals was Pounds 76.7m.
This year's fall is due largely to a poor performance at Christmas, when
Dixons was hit by a price war in computer games. Reported profits are also
expected to be depressed by exceptional costs of up to Pounds 20m to cover
the closure of 100 Currys high street stores this year as the latter's move
into out-of-town superstores accelerates.
Increased profits from Cellnet, the cellular telephone network operator
co-owned with BT, should help Securicor push interim profits beyond last
time's Pounds 29m when it reveals its interim results on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Scottish and Newcastle.
    Greene King.
    MFI Furniture Group.
    Dixons Group.
    Securicor Group.
</CO>
