<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / Al Fresco Living: Outside track
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER KNIGHT and LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More ideas for eating outdoors - some for eating out at home and some, more
transportable, ideas for picnickers:
Plain ebony wooden bowls from Malawi, just wipe clean, no danger of
breaking, Pounds 29.99 each - but they last forever. From the Africa Centre,
38 King Street, London WC2.
Galvanised metal lantern, Pounds 9 from Habitat shops - hang from trees if
eating out at night.
Old-fashioned wire food cover, Pounds 8 and a selection of white porcelain
bottles with cork stopper, ranging from Pounds 7.50 to Pounds 14.50, also
from Habitat.
Make your own night-lights - pack old flower-pots with gravel, put a candle
in the middle and you have a permanently renewable night-light.
A set of four stainless steel stackable cups in a good leather holder,
Pounds 55 from Swaine Adeney, 185 Piccadilly, London W1.
Small, fold-away stool by Muji - just Pounds 7.95 from Muji shops at 26
Great Marlborough Street, London W1 and 39 Shelton Street, London WC2.
Divertimenti, of 45-47 Wigmore Street, London W1 and 139-141 Fulham Road,
London SW3 has a summer mail order brochure (tel: 0252-861212 for a free
copy) which is filled with splendid suggestions for improving life in the
great outdoors.
Hand-held grills (ideal for turning the food and making sure it is cooked
evenly. Fish-shaped holders cost about Pounds 21.50. From most ironmongers.
A galvanised iron bucket filled with citronella-scented wax, perfect for
keeping away the midges. It measures 5in high by 5in diameter and costs
Pounds 12.95.
For lighting the garden how about a sturdy hurricane lantern for Pounds
10.95? From good garden stores and ironmongers.
Mesquite chips to add flavour can be bought by mail for Pounds 3.95 a bag
from Reid &amp; Waterers, The Heath, 462 Staines Road, Middlesex TW4 5DS.
