<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / Finance and the Family: New issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Exco, the money-broking arm of the collapsed British &amp; Commonwealth group,
has launched its return to the stock market after a seven-year absence with
a share offer which values the company at Pounds 215.5m, writes Simon
Davies.
The public is being offered 13.3m shares at a price of 175p, while a further
39.8m shares have been placed with institutions already.
Exco, one of the four major global money-broking businesses, is emerging
from a troubled period under the unsteady guidance of a parent in
receivership. The receivers are selling their remaining 40 per cent holding.
The company has an even profits split between money-broking and fixed income
securities broking, and it has lowered its exposure to individually volatile
markets through a policy of global diversification.
The shares have been issued on an historic price-earnings ratio of 9.5 and a
notional gross yield of 6 per cent, reflecting the apprehension of
volatility attached to the sector.
But Exco's recent record of growth is expected to continue, with interim
profits forecast to rise 28 per cent to Pounds 27.5m.
The offer closes on Friday, July 8, and trading will start on July 19. This
issue is sponsored by NM Rothschild, and the stockbroker is Kleinwort Benson
Securities.
