<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Lacklustre Dow lifted by late
buying flurry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Blue chip stocks benefited yesterday from a late flurry of buying just
before the market closed for long Independence Day weekend, writes Frank
McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 21.69 better at 3,646.65, while
the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was up 1.93 at 446.20. Volume
on the Big Board was light, as many investors decided to begin the holiday a
day early. Only 198m shares were traded.
The secondary markets showed little change, with the American SE inching
0.64 ahead to 424.72, and the Nasdaq composite adding 0.89 to 706.85.
In the previous session, the Dow industrials slid 42 points as the bond
market reacted badly to signs of mounting inflationary pressures in the
manufacturing sector.
Yesterday there was more of the same kind of economic news. The National
Association of Purchasing Management said that its June index of business
activity slipped, while more of its members paid higher prices during the
month. The results mirrored those contained in a regional survey released
Thursday, but investors in neither stocks nor bonds were in the mood for
another sell-off.
The dollar offered some support, gaining ground on the yen, but its recent
erosion remained a peripheral issue for US equity investors. Many of them
were reluctant to make a move until it becomes clear next week whether the
Federal Reserve will lift interest rates next week in support of the
greenback.
At the opening, bargain hunters helped lift the blue chips by nearly 26
points, but the early gains dissolved by midday. Stocks caught a second wind
during the afternoon, and finished strongly.
Among the cyclicals, Alcoa was Dollars 2 3/8 higher at Dollars 75 1/2 and
International Paper climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 67 3/4 . On the
negative side, IBM dropped Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 57.
Profit-taking pushed CBS down Dollars 3 to Dollars 307. A day earlier, the
stock surged on news that the media group was close to an agreement to merge
with QVC, the home-shopping network. QVC receded Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 37
1/4 yesterday. Fresh acquisition news fanned interest in Circus Circus, a
casino operator.
The stock jumped 20.3 per cent, or Dollars 4 3/8 , to Dollars 25 7/8 on a
report that Bally Entertainment was seeking federal approval to take a big
stake in its gaming rival. Bally added Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 6 7/8 .
Venezuela
Caracas picked up 3.7 per cent in a technical adjustment following sharp
falls in recent days. The Merinvest composite index closed 4.7 higher at
133.23, with the benchmark Electricidad de Caracas up 14 bolivars at 333
bolivars. Corimon, the industrial holding was an exception among the
generally firm blue chips, losing 7.50 bolivars to 55.50 bolivars as a
result of a six-for-one dividend share issue.
</TEXT>
