<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / World Commodities Prices: Spices
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The recent decline of the dollar and rise of commodity prices in general
have strengthened many spices markets, reports Man Producten. The currency
effect is straight forward. The relation ship of advances in coffee and oil
and others to spices is more subtle. Farmers and exporters in the source
markets tend to grow and handle a variety of materials. In Indonesia for
example, if coffee is active, the traders naturally concentrate on it.
Cassia which they may also sell, will not be cut or arrive from the
mountains. As a result shortages can develop. Alternatively, farmers may
take profits in coffee and hold spices which appears undervalued in
comparison. The nutmeg and mace markets were steady this week at levels that
remained very low compared with a few years ago, while a shortage of cassia
supplies from the interior of Sumatra kept prices high.
</TEXT>
