<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / International Company News: Richemont to pay Dollars 180m
for Italian pay-TV holding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER and RAY SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Richemont, the Swiss industrial holding company controlled by the South
African Rupert family, is paying Dollars 180m for 25 per cent of Telepiu,
the Italian pay television operator.
The vendor is Compagnie Internationale de Telecommunications.
The acquisition will transform Richemont into a substantial force in
European pay television. It already holds a 46.5 per cent stake in FilmNet,
which broadcasts four pay-TV channels in Holland, Belgium and Scandinavia.
FilmNet has more than 700,000 subscribers.
Telepiu broadcasts throughout Italy two scrambled pay-TV channels featuring
movies and sports events, and one unscrambled channel featuring mainly
documentary and cultural programmes. It has 550,000 subscribers.
Richemont's main existing holdings are controlling stakes in the Rothmans
International tobacco group and the Vendome luxury goods group, built around
the Cartier and Dunhill businesses.
Mr Johann Rupert, managing director, has been attempting to diversify
Richemont's interests, and invested in the lossmaking FilmNet three years
ago together with a South African broadcasting group.
They have overhauled its programming, but losses still rose sharply in the
year ended March, with Richemont's share of the deficit jumping from Pounds
7.3m to Pounds 25.7m (Dollars 35.6m).
Mr Rupert said there was no need for a similar overhaul at Telepiu. However,
he indicated it would take some time to build up the subscription list to a
sufficient level. 'It seems to be endemic in this business - it takes a long
time,' he said.
</TEXT>
