<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 94 / Dockers lose redundancy case
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Twenty-six workers sacked from Goole docks on Humberside after industrial
action lost a four-year battle for redundancy money yesterday.
Three Court of Appeal judges dismissed by a majority an appeal aimed at
reinstating the workers' entitlement to compensation from the Limb group,
their former employer.
The 26 were dismissed in April 1990 after an overtime ban in protest at a
new bonus scheme and said that their sackings were a 'set-up' to avoid
paying redundancy.
The company, which had been taken over by the EIC Group, then decided not to
re-engage its own direct labour force.
Lord Justice Dillon, giving yesterday's majority decision, said that the
industrial action in support of the bonus generated both the dismissal and
the decision to use contract labour.
